default&#xa0;defaultInPatient Flow Manager (IPFM)default6.1default 
defaultThis service is a software-based system that supports clinical best practice through electronic whiteboards and desktop applications, mo
defaultnitoring patient flow and bed availability in real time. 
default&#xa0;default6.2default 
defaultIt records and tracks the status of each patient, sharing this data between departments, clinical staff and administrative functions. This in turn saves time and improves accuracy
default, optimising p
defaultatient journeys, delivering significant savings, and improving patient experience.
default 
default&#xa0;
default6.3default 
defaultAs an example, patient information can be input directly into the electronic system, saving 1,000 clinical hours per annum. It also drives a reduction in average 
defaultlength of stay by 13%
default and 
defaultthe benefit of reduced infection rates through IPFM is equal to 42 QALYs (quality adjusted life years
default), translating to a value of £864k per annum to patients.
default&#xa0;
default“[Hospedia’s] patient flow expertise and understanding of the challen
defaultges involved were compelling factors in our decision to purchase. This system allows us to manage beds in real time down to the individual bed level, free up nursing time to focus on patient care and improve our discharge planning”
default default 
defaultSiobhan Jordan, Deputy defaultDirector of Nursing, Mid Essex NHS Trustdefault&#xa0;
default6.4default 
defaultEast Lancashire NHS Trust has used IPFM for the 
defaultpast
default 
defaultfour
default years to manage patient flow across 1,000 beds in 
defaultfive
default hospitals. In 2013 it decided to utilise
default IPFM to support new CQUIN targets for Dementia Assessmen
defaultts. Within 
defaulttwo
default months of using it, the Trust had completely transformed their performance, consistently over-achieving against the 90% compliance required for each of the three stages of the target, necessary to release the CQUIN funding associated with th
defaulte improvement of dementia assessments.
default&#xa0;defaultEmergency Patient Flow Manager (EPFM)default7.1default 
defaultThere are over 20 million 
defaultadmissions
default at A&amp;
defaultE departments each year across the NHS in England
default and, with pressure on NHS resources rapidly increasing, manual methods of managing patient flows are time consuming and inefficient.
default&#xa0;
default7.2default 
defaultEPFM
default is designed to replace the traditional whiteboard method of tra
defaultcking patient flow from A&amp;E through to admission or discharge. 
default&#xa0;
default7.3default 
defaultLike the 
defaultIPFM
default product
default, the system records and tracks the status of each patient, sharing this data in real time and avoiding the need to locate available beds by telephoning individual 
defaultwards.
default&#xa0;
default7.4default 
defaultIn an example of the service’s broad utility, the effective management of patient flow can help to reduce elective surgery cancellations, alleviating ward bed unavailability, one of the causes of surgery cancellations
default. As approximately a quart
defaulter of patients attending emergency care are subsequently admitted to hospital, tracking the status of these patients is fundamental in managing bed availability. Therefore the value of reducing surgical cancellations, estimated at a 17% reduction
default, represe
defaultnts a benefit of £137k per annum.
default&#xa0;
default7.5default 
defaultEast Cheshire NHS Trust turned to EPFM to deliver a solution 
defaultthat would help 
defaultclinical front line staff manage the four hour wait-time target and enable data capture to support payment-by-results income. Through a clos
defaulte working relationship during the implementation 
defaultand change management process, EPFM has 
defaultgone
default beyond the initial offering, delivering enhanced functionality and increasing staff engagement.
default&#xa0;
default“The [Digital] Whiteboard is the first time we’ve had a visual cl
defaultue as to what’s happening in the department. If you see someone who is starting to near breach point you can follow it up and find out why. Everyone is really keen to use it, because it’s actually fun and easy to operate” 
defaultChristine Scott, Operational Leaddefault Nurse, East Cheshire NHS Trustdefault&#xa0;defaultNovember 2013
